05117nam a22007455i 9780231546645DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017044420  a97802315466457 a10.7312/mcbr186442doi  a(DE-B1597)499070  a(OCoLC)1037351565  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1998.3.L83bM37 2018 7aPER0040102bisacsh04a791.4302/330922231 aMcBride, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow Did Lubitsch Do It? /cJoseph McBride. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b18 film stills  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: “How Did Lubitsch Do It?” -- t1. “Herr Ernst Lubitsch” -- t2. “Who Is Ernst Lubitsch?” -- t3. The “Berlin Style” in Hollywood -- t4. Tin Cans in a Warehouse? -- t5. “Give Me a Moment, Please” -- t6. “In Times Like These ...” -- t7. Master of the Ineffable -- t8. The Aging Master -- t9. The Door Closes -- tEpilogue: The Importance of Being Ernst -- tAcknowledgments and Influences -- tFilmography -- tNotes on Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOrson Welles called Ernst Lubitsch (1892–1947) “a giant” whose “talent and originality are stupefying.” Jean Renoir said, “He invented the modern Hollywood.” Celebrated for his distinct style and credited with inventing the classic genre of the Hollywood romantic comedy and helping to create the musical, Lubitsch won the admiration of his fellow directors, including Alfred Hitchcock and Billy Wilder, whose office featured a sign on the wall asking, “How would Lubitsch do it?” Despite the high esteem in which Lubitsch is held, as well as his unique status as a leading filmmaker in both Germany and the United States, today he seldom receives the critical attention accorded other major directors of his era.How Did Lubitsch Do It? restores Lubitsch to his former stature in the world of cinema. Joseph McBride analyzes Lubitsch’s films in rich detail in the first in-depth critical study to consider the full scope of his work and its evolution in both his native and adopted lands. McBride explains the “Lubitsch Touch” and shows how the director challenged American attitudes toward romance and sex. Expressed obliquely, through sly innuendo, Lubitsch’s risqué, sophisticated, continental humor engaged the viewer’s intelligence while circumventing the strictures of censorship in such masterworks as The Marriage Circle, Trouble in Paradise, Design for Living, Ninotchka, The Shop Around the Corner, and To Be or Not to Be. McBride’s analysis of these films brings to life Lubitsch’s wit and inventiveness and offers revealing insights into his working methods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2018z9783110603088oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2018 Englishz978311060397208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mcbr1864440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231546645/original  a978-3-11-060397-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-